{A very typical plan that works well for White in the Jobava London System is 
the idea of playing Nb5 against ...c5. This is one main difference between the 
Jobava London system and the standard London System: in the standard London 
System White's Knight is much more passive, stuck on b1. In this line we look at 
a few common situation where Nb5 should be considered.} 1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 {Watch 
this Knight dance!} e6 (2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 {is an important line, which is very 
popular and been recommended as a good way for Black to play.} 4. e3 (4. Nb5 $2 
{is premature. This is an instance where you should not play Nb5! Always watch 
out for the check on a5...} 4... Qa5+ {A major problem. White needs a pawn on e3 
for this idea to work, as then the Knight on b5 will be defended by the Bishop 
on f1.}) 4... Nc6 $2 {A couple of IMs have played this against me in Blitz! It 
is practically a losing mistake due to} 5. Nb5 {Black cannot even play ...Na6 
here!} 5... e5 {The best chance, but White is well on his way to winning after} 
6. Bxe5 $18 {.}) 3. Bf4 Nf6 4. e3 (4. Nb5 {is playable, even Jobava has tried 
it, but in the main Jobava-London course I am not recommending this setup. We 
will only be going Nb5 when Black has already moved his c-pawn. Here Black can 
play} 4... Na6 {and ...c6 next, kicking the Knight on b5 away. When Black 
already has a pawn on c5 this idea is not possible.} 5. e3 c6 {and White is 
forced back.}) c5 $6 {[%csl Rc7] A slight mistake already!} 5. Nb5 $1 {[%cal 
Gb5c7,Gf4c7][%csl Rc7] This is a good plan when it forces Black to play ...Na6.} 
Na6 {[%cal Ga6c7,Ga8a7][%csl Ra6,Ra8,Gb5,Gf4] Now Black's Knight on a6 and Rook 
on a8 will have trouble moving. The Rook has to guard a7 while the Knight stops 
Nc7+. White has a very nice hold on the Queenside.} 6. c3 {[%cal Gc3b4][%csl 
Gb5] This is a good version of the standard London as White's Knight is much 
better on the more active b5 square.} Be7 (6... Qb6 7. a4 Be7 {and now we see 
another standard idea that we get to soon.} 8. Nf3 $1 O-O 9. Ne5 $1 {The Knight 
is well placed on e5, a beautiful central square. 1-0 (29) Bauer,C (2630) 
-Berend,F (2346) Maastricht NED 2017}) 7. a4 $14 {[%cal Ga4b5][%csl 
Ra6,Ra8,Gb5,Ga4] Securing the Queenside with an advantage. Black's pieces are 
worse placed compared to White's. White has a strong bind on the Queenside.} *

