{Let's have a look at a game where common ideas found in the Jobava London come 
together.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 (2. Nc3 {is the move order I am suggesting when} 
2... d5 3. Bf4 g6 {transposes to the game.}) g6 3. Nc3 {[%cal Be2e4] Wanting to 
play e2-e4, so Black prevents this.} d5 {[%cal Gd5e4][%csl Ge4]} 4. e3 Bg7 {What 
do we do against ...g6?} 5. h4 $1 {[%cal Bh4h5] Pushing h4-h5 is a very 
promising way to continue against setups with ...g6.} c5 $6 {Premature! What is 
the move we should watch out for when ...c5 has been played?} 6. Nb5 $1 {[%cal 
Gb5c7,Gf4c7][%csl Rc7] This works if Black is forced to play ...Na6. It is not 
so strong otherwise.} Na6 {[%csl Ra6]} 7. a4 {[%csl Gb5] Aiming for the standard 
set-up where all of White's pieces are well protected on the Queenside.} Bf5 {A 
logical developing move.} (7... O-O {was played in another of my games, this 
time against GM Jonathan Hawkins. I continued in standard fashion.} 8. Be2 $5 
(8. c3 {may be more accurate, stopping ...Nb4 and ...Nc6.}) 8... Bd7 (8... Nb4 
$1 {would have been a good move, rerouting the Knight around. That is why White 
should play c3! at some point.}) 9. h5 Qa5+ 10. c3 c4 {Black is maybe winning a 
pawn on the Queenside, but this takes a lot of time. Time that I can use to 
attack on the other side of the board!} 11. Be5 Bxb5 12. axb5 Qxb5 13. Qc2 Ne4 
14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Nf3 Nc7 16. Nd2 Nxd2 17. Qxd2 Ne6 18. b3 $5 Qxb3 19. e4 $5 
{With an attack. This wasn't the best of played games, but it was a rapid game. 
1/2-1/2 (49) Williams, S (2443) - Hawkins, J (2590) London ENG 2016.}) 8. c3 $1 
{[%cal Gc3b4][%csl Ra6] Stopping ...Nb4 and ...Nc6. The a6-Knight is now stuck 
defending the a7-square while the a8-Rook is stuck defending the a7-pawn.} O-O 
9. Be2 $1 {[%cal Bg2g4,Bh4h5] Now Black has to think about g4 and h4.} h5 {What 
now? I have one piece that is not doing anything yet...} 10. Nf3 $1 {[%cal 
Bf3e5][%csl Ge5] Of course! The Knight moves into the centre.} Ng4 {Aimed 
against my plan, but I execute it anyway...} 11. Ne5 $5 {I play it anyway, with 
very aggressive intentions in mind.} Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qd7 13. Rg1 $1 {[%cal Bg2g4] 
You've got to have some fun in life, right!?} Qe6 $2 {A mistake that gives me a 
big attack.} 14. g4 hxg4 15. Bxg4 Bxg4 16. Qxg4 Qxg4 17. Rxg4 Rfd8 18. Ke2 
{[%cal Ba1g1,Bg1h1]} c4 19. h5 $1 {[%cal Ba1g1,Gg1g8][%csl Rg8,Rg7,Rg6] With a 
massive attack along the g-file. 1-0 (46) Williams, S (2443) - Iyengar, I (2008) 
London ENG 2016.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Jobava London System"]
[Site "S&S The Jobava London"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Game: Howell, David"]
[Black "Kasparov, G."]
[Result "1-0"]
[SourceTitle "S&S The Jobava London"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-jobava-london-system/course/29129, variation/5094140"]

{I must thank David Howell for giving me this game. It was a blitz game against 
none other than the great, former World Champion Garry Kasparov. David suggested 
the overall standard of the game wasn't the highest as it was blitz but I can 
comfortably say we would all love to play as well as him in this game and take 
down one of chess's biggest scalps.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c6 {Dare I say 
this is probably not the greatest challenge to White's opening, but in 
Kasparov's defence he has been away from competitive chess for a number of years 
and it demonstrates that even a chess legend can be caught somewhat cold by an 
unexpected opening such as this. That should make any potential player of this 
line very optimistic!} 4. e3 Bf5 5. f3 e6 6. g4 {David knows his stuff and goes 
for the classic Kingside thrust.} Bg6 7. h4 h5 8. g5 Ng8 $14 (8... Nfd7 {is 
arguably better (and is examined in the larger course) but White already has 
what he wants. He has gained space and time on the Kingside and at the same time 
pushed Black's pieces back.}) 9. Bd3 Nd7 (9... Ne7 10. e4 dxe4 11. fxe4 Qxd4 $2 
12. Nb5 $3) 10. Bxg6 $16 {Imagine getting this position from the opening against 
a legend. The Jobava puts another player under the cosh. Black's Kingside 
structure is shattered and he will need to be vigilant for the rest of the game. 
White is assuredly on the front foot.} fxg6 11. Nge2 Bb4 12. Qd3 {Developing 
with threat to the g6-pawn.} Ne7 13. Bh2 {The Bishop vacates the f4-square 
should the e2-Knight wish to occupy it with threats against e6 and g6.} (13. e4 
{was probably the most accurate, dominating the centre and preventing Nf5 before 
Black can gain any sense of counterplay.}) c5 14. a3 c4 15. Qd2 Ba5 16. e4 b5 $6 
{This turns out to be dubious as Black needed to shore up his defences before 
carrying out his counterplay. This move is entirely understandable especially 
from Kasparov who had no desire to sit and wait.} 17. Qe3 O-O 18. O-O Bb6 19. 
Kg2 {Sensibly getting off the diagonal of the b6-bishop. An excellent and 
practical move. Prophylaxis to perfection!} Kh7 20. Rad1 a6 21. Nf4 $16 {The 
totality of White's opening is a success. Black has many problems to overcome.} 
e5 22. Ne6 exd4 23. Rxd4 (23. Qd2 $1 $18 {, as pointed out by David himself, is 
the smoothest way to a material gain when} 23... dxc3 24. Qxc3 {threatens both 
the Queen on d8 and mate on g7. Black would be forced to play} 24... d4 {, and 
after} 25. Rxd4 $3 {Black cannot keep everything together due to the potential 
of moving the d4 Rook and once again threatening g7 with mate.}) Qe8 24. Qd2 Rf7 
25. Nxd5 Nxd5 26. exd5 Bxd4 27. Qxd4 Nf8 28. Nc7 Rxc7 29. Bxc7 Qf7 30. Be5 Nd7 
31. Re1 Re8 32. Bg3 Rxe1 33. Bxe1 Qf5 34. Qe4 Nb6 35. Qxf5 $18 {The rest of the 
game shows how fantastic David's technique is but its outside the scope of this 
course.} gxf5 36. d6 g6 37. Kg3 Kg7 38. Kf4 Nd7 39. Ke3 Kf7 40. Kd4 Ke6 41. Bg3 
Nb8 42. Kc5 Kd7 43. Kd5 Nc6 44. Be1 Nd8 45. Bg3 Nc6 46. c3 Na5 47. Ke5 Nb3 48. 
Kf6 Nc5 49. Kxg6 Nd3 50. Kf7 {A fabulous win for David and a great demonstration 
of the wealth of possibilities which can arise from this opening!} 1-0

