1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {Already taking Black out of mainline theory! This does seem 
similar to a very popular opening, The Italian Game, with 1 e4 e5 2 ♘f3 and 3 
Bc4. We are doing that, but with 1 d4!} d5 3. Bf4 {The starting position for our 
adventures! This bishop is often a great piece as we will see later. One thing I 
love about this opening is that White often gets a good version of the standard 
London System. This is due to the Knight on c3, which is much more of an active 
piece in the Jobava-London System.} c5 4. e3 {This is the soundest reply. White 
now has ideas of Nb5 when Black is forced to play the awkward ...Na6 and his 
Queenside becomes tangled up.} cxd4 5. exd4 e6 6. Nb5 $14 {[%cal 
Gb5c7,Gf1b5][%csl Rc7,Gb5]} Na6 7. c3 {[%cal Gc3b4][%csl Ra6,Gb4] Taking control 
over the b4-square, which guarantees that Black won't free the a6-Knight from 
its offside position anytime soon. If White foregoes playing c3, Black will 
eventually play ...Nh5 (chasing the f4-Bishop off of the h2-b8 diagonal) and 
then ...Nb4.} Be7 8. Bd3 {[%cal Bg1f3,Be1g1] Now White can simply finish 
development with a pleasant position.} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7b5]} 9. a4 $14 {[%cal 
Ga4b5,Gb5a7][%csl Ra8,Ra7,Ra6,Gb5,Ga4] Once again we have the situation where 
White's Knight on b5 controls the whole of Black's Queenside, preventing him 
from untangling.} *

