1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {Already taking Black out of mainline theory! This does seem 
similar to a very popular opening, The Italian Game, with 1 e4 e5 2 ♘f3 and 3 
Bc4. We are doing that, but with 1 d4!} d5 3. Bf4 {The starting position for our 
adventures! This bishop is often a great piece as we will see later. One thing I 
love about this opening is that White often gets a good version of the standard 
London System. This is due to the Knight on c3, which is much more of an active 
piece in the Jobava-London System.} Bf5 4. f3 {Against setups with an early 
...Bf5, I generally recommend trying to make use of the f5-bishop's awkward 
position by advancing with the pawns.} e6 {Alternatives that leave the c8-h3 
diagonal open are discussed in the larger course.} 5. g4 Bg6 6. h4 h6 ({The 
alternative} 6... h5 7. g5 {is looked at in the larger course.}) 7. e3 c5 {This 
runs into a familiar theme.} 8. h5 {[%csl Rg6] First White gains some space at 
the expense of the g6-Bishop.} Bh7 9. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5c7][%csl Rc7,Gb5,Gf4] This 
really is a powerful option which Black should probably not allow. Whenever 
White gets the Knight to b5 (after Black plays ...c5) it dominates Black's 
Queenside, as ...Na6 is the only sensible reply. Simply put, Black is tied up in 
the knots of the Knight on b5 and the Bishop on f4.} Na6 10. c3 {[%cal 
Gc3b4][%csl Gb4] This pawn move is very useful, preventing any future ...Qa5+ or 
...Nb4 ideas.} Be7 11. Bd3 {[%cal Bd3h7][%csl Rh7] Exchanging off Black's best 
minor piece.} Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nd7 {[%cal Ge7g5,Gd8g5] Black was afraid of the 
g4-g5 push.} 13. Ne2 O-O 14. a4 {[%csl Gb5] A strong move, reinforcing the 
Knight's position on b5. It's here to stay for at least a good while yet.} Bf6 
{This allows White to improve the f4-Bishop's position.} 15. Bd6 {[%csl 
Gd6,Rf8]} Re8 16. f4 {[%cal Gf4e5,Bg4g5][%csl Ge5] With a strong grip on the 
centre, as well as ideas of playing g5.} Nb6 $6 17. g5 {Jobava does not need a 
second invitation to take the advantage.} ({The game finished:} 17. g5 17... 
hxg5 18. h6 $1 g6 19. fxg5 Bxg5 20. h7+ Kg7 21. Be5+ f6 $6 22. Nd6 $5 Rh8 $2 23. 
Nf4 Bxf4 {The Knight had to go, but now Black's Kingside will be fatally levered 
open in any case.} 24. Bxf4 g5 25. O-O-O Nc4 26. Rh6 $5 Kxh6 27. Nf7+ Kg7 28. 
Nxd8 Raxd8 29. b3 $6 Nb6 30. Rg1 Rxh7 31. e4 Kh8 $6 32. e5 $1 gxf4 $2 33. Qg6 
Rf8 34. exf6 {1-0 Jobava, B. (2713) - Mamedyarov, S. (2743), Wch Rapid Dubai 
2014 (3) 1-0}) *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Jobava London System"]
[Site "S&S The Jobava London"]
