1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {Already taking Black out of mainline theory! This does seem 
similar to a very popular opening, The Italian Game, with 1 e4 e5 2 ♘f3 and 3 
♘c4. We are doing that, but with 1 d4!} e6 3. Bf4 {In the larger course I also 
take a look at 3. e4, which likely transposes to a French Defense - Black may 
not be ready to play that opening!} Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Rc3] My experience 
tells me that a lot of players are concerned about how to meet this move and 
other lines with ...Bb4. This is understandable. Black pins the c3-Knight and 
has various options, including taking on c3 and ...Nd5 or ...Ne4. White should 
respect this line, but I also feel that by being prepared and understanding the 
position it should not be feared.} 4. e3 {This is the choice of Jobava.} Nd5 
{[%csl Rc3,Rf4] This move can look dangerous for White and avoids transpositions 
into lines already covered by not playing 4... d5.} 5. Nge2 {[%cal Ge2c3,Ge2f4] 
This is a necessary reply. I am going to focus on what looks to be Black's best 
option which is when he captures the Bishop on f4.} Nxf4 6. exf4 O-O {Black can 
play other moves and set-ups e.g. 6... b6 and 6... d5, but I want to focus on 
White's plans and positions.} 7. a3 {[%csl Rb4]} Be7 8. g3 {[%cal 
Bf1g2,Gd4e5,Gf4e5][%csl Ge5]} ({This is a conservative approach whereas Jobava 
himself played} 8. d5 {in this position. However, I see nothing wrong with 
keeping tensions down here.}) d5 9. Bg2 {[%cal 
Be1g1,Bh1e1,Ba1d1,Bd1d3,Gd4e5,Gf4e5][%csl Ge5,Rc8] The prospects are roughly 
even. White will castle short, develop his Queen, centralise his Rooks preparing 
for the key battleground which in this position is in the centre.} *

