1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {Already taking Black out of mainline theory! This does seem 
similar to a very popular opening, The Italian Game, with 1 e4 e5 2 ♘f3 and 3 
♘c4. We are doing that, but with 1 d4!} d5 3. Bf4 g6 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 {[%cal 
Bh4h5] This is generally what we play against ...g6 setups. White is well placed 
to advance the h-pawn.} h5 6. Nf3 {[%cal Bf3e5][%csl Ge5,Rf7,Rg6] Now that Black 
has weakened his Kingside pawns, our Knight will be well placed on e5.} Bg4 
{[%cal Gg4d1][%csl Rf3,Rd1]} 7. Qd2 {[%cal Bf3e5]} Bxf3 8. gxf3 {[%cal 
Be3e4,Bh1g1,Gg1g7,Be1c1] The f3-pawn can support the e4-advance, and White can 
utilize the half-open g-file to attack Black's King.} Nc6 (8... O-O {is featured 
in a model game in the larger course.}) 9. O-O-O O-O 10. e4 $14 {[%cal 
Bc1b1,Be4e5,Bh1g1,Bf4h6,Bh6g7][%csl Rg8,Rg7] This position is comfortably better 
for White: better development, piece placement and control of the centre. White 
may continue with moves such as Kb1, e5 and perhaps Bh6.} *

