1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {Already taking Black out of mainline theory! This does seem 
similar to a very popular opening, The Italian Game, with 1 e4 e5 2 ♘f3 and 3 
♘c4. We are doing that, but with 1 d4!} g6 3. Bf4 {This works best for our 
opening.} Bg7 (3... d5 {transposes to the previous 3... g6 lines}) {.} 4. e4 
{[%cal Bd1d2,Bf4h6,Bh2h4] And why not! It seems so logical to take over the 
centre. White is now planning to stop Black from playing ...e5 and mate Black on 
the h-file, with the standard plan Bh6, O-O-O, h4 etc.! Take a look at the 
explanations and lines in the larger course to see what I say about how White 
should stop ...e5.} (4. Qd2 {is also interesting, but} 4... d5 {may be a good 
response that takes us out of our repertoire.}) O-O 5. e5 $1 {[%csl Rf6]} ({I 
was going to suggest the simple move} 5. Nf3 {, but then I found the interesting 
novelty} 5... d5 $5 6. exd5 c6 $1 {which looks dangerous for White. 5. e5! is 
also just a strong move that gives White an advantage.}) Nh5 {In the words of 
Ben Finegold - 'suspicious'. What a hero that guy is.} 6. Bd2 $1 {[%cal 
Bg2g4,Bc7c5,Bc5d4][%csl Rh5,Gd2] The Bishop gets out of the way of ...c5 and 
...cxd4 when the Bishop on e3 is attacked. There is now no good way for Black to 
avoid g4 when his Knight is trapped!} c5 (6... Bh8 {and 7... Ng7 is too ugly to 
be considered.}) 7. g4 {[%csl Rh5]} cxd4 8. Nce2 {[%cal Bg4h5] The point of 
putting the Bishop on d2.} Nc6 9. gxh5 $18 {[%cal Be2g3,Bg1f3,Bf1d3,Be1g1] I 
simply do not believe that Black has enough compensation here. White is a piece 
up with no real weaknesses. Just develop and get that King safe.} *

