1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {Already taking Black out of mainline theory! This does seem 
similar to a very popular opening, The Italian Game, with 1 e4 e5 2 ♘f3 and 3 
♘c4. We are doing that, but with 1 d4!} g6 3. Bf4 {This works best for our 
opening.} Bg7 (3... d5 {transposes to the previous 3... g6 lines.}) 4. e4 {And 
why not! It seems so logical to take over the centre. White is now planning to 
stop Black from playing ...e5 and mate Black on the h-file, with the standard 
plan Bh6, O-O-O, h4 etc.! Take a look at the explanations and lines in the 
larger course to see what I say about how White should stop ...e5.} (4. Qd2 {is 
also interesting, but} 4... d5 {may be a good response that takes us out of our 
repertoire.}) d5 $5 {[%cal Gd5e4][%csl Re4] This is an interesting way to try 
and gain some active counterplay against White's strong centre.} 5. e5 {[%csl 
Ge5,Gd4,Rg7] Positionally correct. The pawn on e5 is a powerhouse that blocks 
out Black's Bishop on g7.} Ne4 6. Nxe4 {Let's not let that Knight linger for too 
long.} dxe4 7. Bc4 $1 {[%cal Gc4f7][%csl Gc4] This logical developing move seems 
best. The Bishop swings into play on an active square. I would prefer to be in 
White's shoes here as Black has to be quite careful playing against the two 
central pawns.} c5 {[%cal Bc5d4,Bb8c6,Bc8g4] This break will have to be played 
at some point, otherwise those pawns are just too strong.} 8. dxc5 $1 {[%csl 
Gc5,Ge5] Otherwise Black gets good play against the pawns with ...Nc6 and 
...Bg4. This keeps some pressure against Black's position.} O-O 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. 
c3 {[%cal Bb2b4] Preparing b4 in some situations.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e5,Gg7e5]} 11. 
e6 $1 {The key move. This pawn will be lost anyway, so why not do some damage to 
Black's position in the process?} Bxe6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Ne2 {[%cal 
Bb2b4,Ba2a4,Ba1d1][%csl Re4,Re6,Re7] I am sure most players would prefer to be 
White here. White can aim for simplifications and then use his Queenside pawn 
majority to make a Queen. Easy really...} *

