1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {Already taking Black out of mainline theory! This does seem 
similar to a very popular opening, The Italian Game, with 1 e4 e5 2 ♘f3 and 3 
♘c4. We are doing that, but with 1 d4!} g6 3. Bf4 {This works best for our 
opening.} Bg7 (3... d5 {transposes to the previous 3... g6 lines.}) 4. e4 {And 
why not! It seems so logical to take over the centre. White is now planning to 
stop Black from playing ...e5 and mate Black on the h-file, with the standard 
plan Bh6, O-O-O, h4 etc.! Take a look at the explanations and lines in the 
larger course to see what I say about how White should stop ...e5.} (4. Qd2 {is 
also interesting, but} 4... d5 {may be a good response that takes us out of our 
repertoire.}) d6 {The first thing that most people have said to me about this 
position is, 'This is just a Pirc/Modern defence!?'. Well, yes and no! I will 
let you into a little secret that I heard from a good 'informant'. Magnus stated 
that this line with Bf4 is one of the reasons he doesn't go into this position 
as Black. He feels it is very bad for Black. Not sure if that piece of 
information is true or not, but I totally agree with it! This position looks 
very positive for White. It is not a normal Pirc or Modern as Black has messed 
his move order up by playing ...Nf6 and ...Bg7 too early. This is a problem for 
Black as now he cannot play ...e5! easily, which is a move he would love to 
play.} 5. Qd2 {[%cal Be1c1,Bf4h6,Bh2h4,Bh4h5]} Nc6 {[%cal Be7e5] This seems 
best. Black actively aims to play ...e5 - a move that we are well positioned to 
stop, or at least discourage.} 6. O-O-O {[%cal Gd1d8][%csl Gd2,Gd1,Rd8] 
Preventing e5. White continues to do this for the next few moves.} O-O 7. Nf3 
{[%cal Gf3e5][%csl Ge5] Against ...Nc6 this is best as it helps control e5, 
which is a key square.} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1,Be7e5] Again fighting for ...e5. Other 
moves allow ideas such as h4 or Be2 first and then h4/Bh6.} 8. Qe3 $1 {[%cal 
Gd1d8,Be7e5,Bd4e5,Bd6e5][%csl Rd8] This looks very clear to me. The Queen slides 
out of the way of the Rook on d1 and in the process stops ...e5. Black may be ok 
here, but as we saw in the 'informational' game he has to be very careful.} Nd7 
$6 {An understandable but passive move.} 9. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Gg5d8][%csl Rd8,Re7]} 
(9. Bh6 {is most likely good as well, but this is a cute way to stop Black's 
plans.}) Qe8 {Black is desperate to play ...e5.} 10. Bh6 {Only now that the 
Queen has misplaced itself.} Bxf3 11. gxf3 $1 {[%cal Bh1g1,Gg1g8][%csl Gf3,Ge4] 
Another good move. Let's open the g-file and bring another pawn to the centre.} 
e5 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. dxe5 $1 Qxe5 14. Nd5 {[%cal Gd5c7,Bf3f4,Bh2h4,Bh4h5][%csl 
Rc7] White has a great attacking position with f4 and h4 as likely follow ups.} 
*

